# Architecture & Separation of Concerns

## Layer Diagram

```
PDF/CSV/Image
     ↓
[ Parser ]              src/lib/parseStatement.ts, src/lib/csv-import.ts
     ↓ ParsedStatementData (JSON)
[ API Route ]           src/app/api/parse/route.ts  ← only layer that writes parsedData
     ↓
[ Firestore ]           statements/{id}.parsedData
     ↓
[ Aggregation ]         src/lib/consolidate.ts, src/lib/extractTransactions.ts
     ↓
[ Financial Profile ]   src/lib/financialProfile.ts  ← SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH for all spending data
     ↓ FinancialProfileCache (cached in users/{uid}/financialProfile)
[ Business Rules ]      src/lib/applyRules.ts, src/lib/spendingMetrics.ts
     ↓
[ UI / API Routes ]     src/app/account/**, src/app/api/user/**
                        ALL pages read from getFinancialProfile() — never from extractAllTransactions() directly

                    ── orthogonal, event-driven layer ──

[ Insights Layer ]  src/lib/insights/
     ↑ fireInsightEvent(event, uid, db)   ← called fire-and-forget from parse/route.ts
     │                                      or explicitly from POST /api/user/insights/generate
     ├─ registry.ts     maps event types → detectors
     ├─ pipeline.ts     orchestrates: detectors → AI writer → persist cards
     │                  also calls buildAndCacheFinancialProfile() to warm the cache
     └─ detectors/      one file per domain (subscriptions, cashflow, alert, savings…)
          writes to: users/{uid}/subscriptions, users/{uid}/agentInsights, users/{uid}.financialDNA
          NEVER writes to: statements/{id}.parsedData
```

## Rules

### 1. Parser is read-only
- `parseStatement.ts` and CSV import helpers MUST NOT import from `firebase-admin` or any DB client.
- The parser receives raw bytes and returns `ParsedStatementData` JSON. Nothing else.

### 2. Only API routes write to the database
- DB reads/writes live exclusively in `src/app/api/**` route handlers.
- `src/lib/**` modules are pure functions — they accept and return plain data.

### 3. Standard data contract
- All data passed between layers uses `ParsedStatementData` (and its sub-types) from `src/lib/types.ts`.
- Never invent ad-hoc shapes inside a route and pass them raw to another layer.

### 4. Business rules are separate from aggregation
- `applyRules.ts` applies user category rules to already-parsed data. It MUST NOT re-parse or call the DB.
- `consolidate.ts` aggregates multiple `ParsedStatementData` objects. It MUST NOT apply UI logic.

### 5. Cross-layer changes require permission
- If a fix requires modifying **two or more layers** (e.g. parser + DB route, or aggregation + UI), 
  stop and ask the user for permission before writing any code.

### 6. Income is never modified by expense rules
- `applyRulesAndRecalculate` (business rules layer) only touches `expenses`. 
- `income` data is owned by the parser output and must be preserved as-is through aggregation.

### 7. AI extraction layer — review required before any change
The AI extraction layer consists of:
- `src/lib/parseStatement.ts` — `SYSTEM_PROMPT`, `normalizeData`, `parseJsonResponse`, `extractJson`

**Do NOT modify this layer without explicit user review**, because:
- The prompt defines the data contract (field names, categories, JSON shape) between the AI and all downstream code.
- Changes to `SYSTEM_PROMPT` affect every statement ever re-parsed; old Firestore data becomes inconsistent.
- `normalizeData` is the single source of truth for all derived totals — silent bugs here corrupt all financial figures.

### 8. Firestore write layer — review required before any change
The Firestore write layer consists of:
- `src/app/api/parse/route.ts` — writes `parsedData` to `statements/{id}`
- `src/app/api/upload/route.ts` — creates the statement document and enforces duplicate detection
- `src/app/api/user/csv-import/route.ts` — writes CSV-sourced transactions

**Do NOT modify this layer without explicit user review**, because:
- These are the only paths that persist financial data; bugs here silently corrupt or lose user data.
- Deduplication logic (`txFingerprint`) lives here and must match across PDF and CSV paths.
- The `status` field lifecycle (`processing → completed | error`) is relied upon by every read query.

### 9. `parsedData` ownership — only two legitimate writers
`statements/{id}.parsedData` may only be written by:

1. **AI extraction pipeline** — `src/app/api/parse/route.ts` after a successful AI parse.
2. **User-initiated updates** — e.g. `PATCH /api/user/statements/[id]` when the user explicitly re-categorizes transactions or applies a rule.

**Never write to `parsedData` from:**
- Background jobs or pipelines (insights generation, agent pipeline, DNA inference)
- Aggregation/consolidation code (`consolidate.ts`, `applyRules.ts` in-memory use is fine)
- Any automated process the user did not directly trigger

Category rules are applied **in-memory at read time** by the consolidated route — they do not need to be baked back into Firestore unless the user explicitly triggers a re-categorization.

### 10. Insights layer is isolated from extraction and ingestion

The insights layer (`src/lib/insights/`) is a separate, orthogonal concern:
- It is **never imported by** `parseStatement.ts`, `consolidate.ts`, `applyRules.ts`, or any ingestion route.
- The only connection from the ingestion side is a single fire-and-forget call in `parse/route.ts`:
  ```ts
  fireInsightEvent({ type: "statement.parsed" }, uid, db).catch(console.error)
  ```
- Insights write exclusively to `users/{uid}/agentInsights`, `users/{uid}/subscriptions`, and `users/{uid}.financialDNA`.
- **Never** write `parsedData` or any field on `statements/{id}` from the insights layer.

### 11. Financial Profile is the single source of truth for all spending data

All API routes and pages that need spending, income, or balance data **must** call
`getFinancialProfile(uid, db)` from `src/lib/financialProfile.ts`. Direct calls to
`extractAllTransactions()` from routes or UI are not allowed.

**Why:** `getFinancialProfile` is the single computation path that:
- Applies user category rules to every transaction
- Enforces `CORE_EXCLUDE_RE` consistently (transfers excluded, all other expenses included)
- Filters out invalid data (negative-amount expense transactions)
- Pre-computes `typicalMonthly` (median/avg) and `monthlyHistory` for all months
- Caches results in `users/{uid}/financialProfile` so every route sees identical numbers

**Cache freshness strategy — Time + Version + Schema:**
- `< 5 min` old → return immediately (hot path)
- `5 min – 24 h` → check source version hash; rebuild only if statements changed
- `> 24 h` → always rebuild
- `schemaVersion` mismatch → always rebuild (bump `SCHEMA_VERSION` in `financialProfile.ts` when computation logic changes)

**Cache invalidation triggers:**
- Statement parsed → `insights/pipeline.ts` calls `buildAndCacheFinancialProfile`
- Category rule saved → `category-rules/route.ts` calls `invalidateFinancialProfileCache`
- Manual refresh → any caller invokes `buildAndCacheFinancialProfile` directly

**`CORE_EXCLUDE_RE`** in `src/lib/spendingMetrics.ts` is the single definition of what
"Excl. transfers" means. Currently: inter-account transfers only (`transfers`, `transfers & payments`).
Debt payments, investments, and all other categories are counted as real spending.
Do not change this regex without user review — it affects every spending total everywhere.

### 12. External Data Layer is orthogonal — `getFinancialProfile` is its only dependency

```
[ Scheduled Job ]        POST /api/cron/refresh-external-data  (daily/weekly)
     ↓
[ External Data Layer ]  src/lib/external/
     ├─ fetchers/        one file per data source (Bank of Canada, FRED, etc.)
     ├─ store.ts         read/write  externalData/{dataType}  in Firestore (global, not per-user)
     ├─ registry.ts      maps dataType → { country, relevant(profile) }
     └─ pipeline.ts      for each affected user:
                           1. getFinancialProfile(uid, db)   ← ONLY dependency on other layers
                           2. relevance check (country + account types)
                           3. emit signal if relevant → persist to users/{uid}/agentInsights
```

**Rules:**
- The external data layer MUST NOT import from `parseStatement.ts`, `consolidate.ts`,
  `extractAllTransactions.ts`, `insights/`, or any ingestion route.
- Its only permitted cross-layer call is `getFinancialProfile(uid, db)`.
- Global market/rate data lives in `externalData/{dataType}` — one document per data type,
  shared across all users. Never stored per-user.
- Relevance is checked at pipeline time, not at fetch time. Fetch first, filter per user second.
- Country is auto-detected from `profile.accountSnapshots` bank names (TD/RBC/BMO → CA;
  Chase/BofA → US). A user-set `profile.country` field overrides auto-detection when added.

**To add a new external data source:**
1. Add a fetcher in `src/lib/external/fetchers/<source>.ts`
2. Register it in `src/lib/external/registry.ts` with its `country` and `relevant()` function
3. Nothing else in the codebase needs to change

### 13. Detector pattern — how to add a new insight domain

Each insight domain is a single file implementing `InsightDetector` (from `src/lib/insights/types.ts`).

**To add a new detector:**
1. Create `src/lib/insights/detectors/<domain>.ts`
2. Implement the `InsightDetector` interface:
   ```ts
   export const myDetector: InsightDetector = {
     name: "my-domain",
     handles: ["statement.parsed", "full.refresh"],   // which events trigger it
     minMonths: 3,                                     // skip if not enough data
     async run(ctx, event): Promise<DetectedSignal[]> {
       // detect signals from ctx.expenseTxns / ctx.incomeTxns
       // may write to insights-owned Firestore collections
       // return DetectedSignal[] — facts only, no prose
     },
   };
   ```
3. Import and add it to `ALL_DETECTORS` in `src/lib/insights/registry.ts`.

That is the only change required. Nothing else in the codebase needs to know about the new detector.

**Detector rules:**
- Return `DetectedSignal[]` — quantified facts, no card prose (AI or code writers handle that).
- Gate on `minMonths` — do not generate low-confidence signals with insufficient history.
- Respect `lockedFields` on any master data records (subscriptions, etc.) the user has explicitly set.
- Never touch `parsedData`.

### 14. App features are isolated consumers of the financial engine

New product features — Events, Reminders, Life Log, Tags, and anything built in the future —
are **separate, orthogonal apps** that sit on top of the financial engine. They MUST follow
these rules:

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                  APPS (features)                    │
│  Events  │  Reminders  │  Life Log  │  AI Chat  │  │
│  Goals   │  Forecast   │  Sharing   │  Tags     │  │
└──────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────┘
                       │ reads only via getFinancialProfile()
                       ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│            FINANCIAL ENGINE (read-only API)         │
│  getFinancialProfile()  │  extractTransactions()    │
│  consolidate()          │  applyRules()             │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**Rules:**
- App features read from `getFinancialProfile(uid, db)` — this is the only permitted
  dependency on the financial engine.
- App features write ONLY to their own Firestore collections under `users/{uid}/`
  (e.g. `users/{uid}/events`, `users/{uid}/txTags`, `users/{uid}/reminders`).
- Engine files (`parseStatement.ts`, `consolidate.ts`, `applyRules.ts`,
  `financialProfile.ts`, `spendingMetrics.ts`) MUST NOT import from any app feature.
- The engine has zero knowledge that any app feature exists.
- If an app feature is removed, the engine and all other features continue working unchanged.
- Transaction annotations (tags, notes, event links) are stored in the app's own
  collections and joined in-memory at the API route layer — never written back to
  `statements/{id}.parsedData`.
